STABLECOINS
 What are Stablecoins?
üîπ Simple definition
Stablecoins are cryptocurrencies designed to maintain a stable value by being pegged to a real-world asset such as a fiat currency (USD, INR), commodity (gold), or a basket of assets.
Unlike Bitcoin or Ethereum, stablecoins do not fluctuate heavily in price.
üîπ Why stablecoins were created (The core problem)
‚ùå Problem with cryptocurrencies
	‚Ä¢	Bitcoin & others are highly volatile
	‚Ä¢	Difficult to use for:  
 
	‚Ä¢	Payments
	‚Ä¢	Salaries
	‚Ä¢	Savings
	‚Ä¢	Accounting
‚úÖ Solution
Create a blockchain-based digital currency with:
	‚Ä¢	Price stability
	‚Ä¢	Fast settlement
	‚Ä¢	Global transfer
	‚Ä¢	No central bank control (in most cases)
This led to Stablecoins
Who introduced Stablecoins & When?
There is no single inventor, but development happened in stages.
üîπ First widely recognized stablecoin
‚úÖ Tether (USDT)
	‚Ä¢	Introduced: 2014
	‚Ä¢	Original name: Realcoin
	‚Ä¢	Founders: Brock Pierce, Reeve Collins, Craig Sellars
	‚Ä¢	Peg: 1 USDT = 1 USD
This marked the birth of modern stablecoins


